    <subsection xml:id="definitions-functions-exponential">
        <title>Definitions</title>
        <definition>
            <title>Exponential Function</title>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    For any real number <m>x</m>, an <term>exponential function</term> is a function of the form <m>f(x) = a \cdot b^x</m> where
                    <ul>
                        <li><m>a</m> is a non-zero real number</li>
                        <li><m>b</m> is any positive real number, where <m>b \neq 1</m></li>
                    </ul>
                    Exponential functions grow or decay with a constant <em>percent</em> rate of change.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </definition>

        <definition>
            <title>Key Characteristics of Exponential Functions</title>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    For an exponential function <m>f(x) = a \cdot b^x</m>, with <m>a \gt 0</m> and <m>b \gt 0</m>, <m>b \neq 1</m>, we have the following:
                    <ul>
                        <li><m>(0,a)</m> is the vertical intercept.</li>
                        <li>There is no horizontal intercept.</li>
                        <li>The domain of <m>f</m> is <m>(-\infty, \infty)</m>.</li>
                        <li>The range of <m>f</m> is <m>(0, \infty)</m>.</li>
                        <li><m>f</m> is a one-to-one function.</li>
                        <li>The horizontal asymptote is <m>y = 0</m>.</li>
                        <li><p>If <m>b \gt 1</m>, then <m>f</m> is an increasing function and
                                <ul>
                                    <li>as <m>x \to \infty</m>, <m>f(x) \to \infty</m>, and</li>
                                    <li>as <m>x \to -\infty</m>, <m>f(x) \to 0</m>.</li>
                                </ul>
                            </p>
                            <figure xml:id="fig-definitions-functions-exponential-growth">
                                <caption><m>y = a \cdot b^x, b \gt 1</m></caption>
                                <image width="60%">
                                    <description>
                                        <p>
                                            Graph of an exponentially increasing function. 
                                            The curve begins very close to the <m>x</m>-axis, 
                                            passes through the point <m>(0,a)</m>, 
                                            then curves sharply upward off of the graph to the right.
                                        </p>
                                    </description>
                                    <latex-image>
                                            \begin{tikzpicture}
                                            \begin{axis}[
                                            framedaxes,
                                            height=5cm,
                                            width=5cm,
                                            xlabel={$x$},
                                            ylabel={$y$},
                                            xmin=-6,xmax=6,
                                            ymin=-6,ymax=6,
                                            xtick={-16,16},
                                            minor xtick={-16,16},
                                            ytick={-16,16},
                                            minor ytick={-16,16},
                                            grid=both
                                            ]
                                            \addplot+[first,smooth,domain=-6:2.584] {2^x};
                                            \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,1)};
                                            \node at (axis cs:-1.5,1.5) {{\tiny $(0,a)$}};									
                                            \end{axis}
                                            \end{tikzpicture}
                                    </latex-image>
                                </image>
                            </figure>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>If <m>0 \lt b \lt 1</m>, then <m>f</m> is a decreasing function and
                            <ul>
                                <li>as <m>x \to \infty</m>, <m>f(x) \to 0</m>, and</li>
                                <li>as <m>x \to -\infty</m>, <m>f(x) \to \infty</m>.</li>
                            </ul>
                            </p>
                            <figure xml:id="fig-definitions-functions-exponential-decay">
                                <caption><m>y = a \cdot b^x, 0 \lt b \lt 1</m></caption>
                                <image width="60%">
                                    <description>
                                        <p>
                                            Graph of an exponentially decreasing function. 
                                            From the left the curve comes down from the top of the graph, 
                                            passes through the point <m>(0,a)</m>, 
                                            then levels off near the <m>x</m>-axis.
                                        </p>
                                    </description>
                                    <latex-image>
                                            \begin{tikzpicture}
                                            \begin{axis}[
                                            framedaxes,
                                            height=5cm,
                                            width=5cm,
                                            xlabel={$x$},
                                            ylabel={$y$},
                                            xmin=-6,xmax=6,
                                            ymin=-6,ymax=6,
                                            xtick={-16,16},
                                            minor xtick={-16,16},
                                            ytick={-16,16},
                                            minor ytick={-16,16},
                                            grid=both
                                            ]
                                            \addplot+[first,smooth,domain=-2.584:6] {2^(-x)};
                                            \addplot[soliddot] coordinates {(0,1)};
                                            \node at (axis cs:1.5,1.5) {{\tiny $(0,a)$}};									
                                            \end{axis}
                                            \end{tikzpicture}
                                    </latex-image>
                                </image>
                            </figure>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </definition>
            <example>
                <p>
                    <url href="https://www.desmos.com/calculator/zcp3gaj5ws" visual="https://tiny.cc/111Z-ExpFunction">View this Desmos graph</url> to see an interactive example of an exponential function.
                </p>
            </example>

        <definition>
            <title>The Number <m>e</m></title>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    The number <m>e</m> was discovered in the late 1600's by Jacob Bernoulli. Later in the 1700's, Leonard Euler discovered many of its interesting properties.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>e</m> can be approximated by <m>2.718281828459</m>, though its decimal form does not end and does not repeat. It is an irrational number. 
                </p>
                <p>
                    The graph of the function given by <m>f(x) = e^x</m> looks a lot like the graphs of the functions given by <m>g(x) = 1^x</m> and <m>h(x) = 3^x</m>, as shown in <xref ref="fig-definitions-exponentials-e"/>.
                </p>
                <figure xml:id="fig-definitions-exponentials-e">
                    <caption><m>y=e^x</m></caption>
                    <image>
                        <description>
                            <p>
                                The graph of the curve <m>y = e^x</m> is drawn in between the graphs of <m>y = 2^x</m> and <m>y = 3^x</m>, 
                                rising more sharply than the former but not as sharply as the latter.
                            </p>
                        </description>
                        <latex-image>
                            <![CDATA[
                                \begin{tikzpicture}
                                \begin{axis}[
                                framedaxes,
                                legend pos=north west,
                                legend cell align=left,
                                height=6.5cm,
                                width=7cm,
                                xlabel={$x$},
                                ylabel={$y$},
                                xmin=-4,xmax=4,
                                ymin=-1,ymax=7,
                                grid=both,
                                xtick={-3,-2,...,3},
                                ytick={0,1,...,6},
                                ]
                                \addplot+[third!35,dashed,domain=-4:2.807354,smooth]{2^x};
                                \addplot+[first,domain=-4:1.945910,smooth]{2.718281828^x};
                                \addplot+[second,dashed,domain=-4:1.771243,smooth]{3^x};
                                \legend{$y=2^x$, $y=e^x$, $y=3^x$}
                                \end{axis}
                                \end{tikzpicture}
                                ]]>
                        </latex-image>
                    </image>
                </figure>
            </statement>
        </definition>
    </subsection>

